        <section id="Hazur Sahib" class="section">
            <h2>Hazur Sahib</h2>
            <img src="nanded.jpg" alt="Hazur Sahib" class="section-image">
            <p>Hazur Sahib, also known as Takht Sachkhand Sri Hazur Abchalnagar Sahib, is a prominent Gurudwara and one of the five Takhts (seats of authority) in Sikhism, located in Nanded, Maharashtra. It holds immense religious significance as the site where Guru Gobind Singh, the tenth Sikh Guru, spent his final days and ultimately departed from this world. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Kandhar Fort" class="section">
            <h2>Kandhar Fort</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Kandhar Fort" class="section-image">
            <p>Kandhar Fort, located in the town of Kandhar in the Nanded district of Maharashtra, is a historical fort attributed to the Rashtrakuta King Krishna III of Malkhed. It served as the capital of the mighty Rashtrakuta Empire, which ruled the Deccan between the 6th and 10th centuries CE. The fort's impressive architecture features a 12-meter wall and 18 watchtowers, surrounded by a water-filled ditch for added protection. While the original structure was likely smaller, the fort you see today boasts additions from various dynasties, including the Bahmani sultans in the 14th century, showcasing a blend of Indo-Islamic styles. Inside, remnants of Ambar Khana and Sheesh Mahal, featuring beautiful glass work and elements like hot and cold water storage facilities, hint at the fort's royal past. Beyond its architectural splendor, Kandhar Fort is also famous as a major Jain center during the Rashtrakuta period, with a broken statue of Kshetrapala, a Jain deity, estimated to have been over 50 feet tall based on a surviving toenail. The fort is situated approximately 40 km from Nanded Junction railway station and can be accessed by bus and rickshaw. Visitors are welcomed to explore the fort and its historical charm, with the winter months (October to February) being the ideal time to visit when the weather is mild and pleasant. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Sahastrakund Waterfall" class="section">
            <h2>Sahastrakund Waterfall</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Sahastrakund Waterfall" class="section-image">
            <p>The Sahastrakund Waterfall, located on the Painganga River in Maharashtra, India, is a natural attraction known for its scenic beauty, cultural significance, and diverse ecosystem. The name "Sahastrakund" means "thousand ponds," referring to the many small pools around the waterfall. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Kaleshwar Temple" class="section">
            <h2>Kaleshwar Temple</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Kaleshwar Temple" class="section-image">
            <p>The Kaleshwar Mandir in Vishnupuri, Nanded, Maharashtra, is a centuries-old Hindu temple dedicated to Lord Shiva, known for its spiritual ambiance and location on the banks of the Godavari River. Legend has it that the temple was established 700 to 800 years ago after a natural lingam, an emblem of Shiva, was discovered at this spot by a brahmin. The temple's name, Kaleshwar, refers to the black idol of Lord Shiva enshrined within the sanctum sanctorum. The temple's architecture blends South Indian and Marathi styles, featuring a pillared roof with carvings depicting scenes from the Ramayana and Mahabharata. The temple is a significant pilgrimage site in Nanded and draws devotees, particularly during festivals like Shravana, Maha Shivaratri, and Navratri. Visitors can also enjoy the scenic surroundings, including boating on the Godavari River and witnessing the daily Godavari Aarti performed from 6 PM to 7 PM. The temple is wheelchair-accessible with available parking, making it convenient for visitors of all abilities. The Kaleshwar Temple offers a blend of historical, architectural, and spiritual experiences for devotees and tourists alike. </p>
        </section>

        <section id="Malegaon Jat Temple" class="section">
            <h2>Malegaon Jat Temple</h2>
            <img src="https://encrypted-tbn0.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcQhg9rAmI81ey7yb1F829bN7KJ1-eN7Cq4kuQrEeorz633Zuy0h5L7hfutU-tIXTsWBtFE&usqp=CAU" alt="Malegaon Jat Temple" class="section-image">
            <p>Several notable temples exist in Malegaon, Nanded district, Maharashtra, each contributing to the town's religious landscape and attracting devotees and tourists alike. One of the most prominent is the Shri Kshetra Khandoba Mandir, dedicated to Lord Khandoba. Built in the Hemadpanti architectural style, the temple features a large courtyard and is renowned for the annual Malegaon Yatra, a grand fair held during the month of Margashirsh. This five-day festival is a significant cultural event, drawing thousands for religious ceremonies, processions, music, dance, and a bustling animal market known for its horses, donkeys, and camels. Another important temple is the Jhanjheshwar Mahadev Temple, a historic site dedicated to Lord Shiva, located near the Mausam River. Additionally, Malegaon is home to the Shree Balaji Mandir, known for its cleanliness and well-maintained premises, offering Prasad (food) to the needy. Other temples within Malegaon include the Rokdoba Hanumaan Mandir and the Sarveshwar Mahadev Temple, which attracts a significant number of devotees. Beyond being places of worship, these temples act as vibrant centers of community life, hosting cultural events, educational programs, and social gatherings, fostering a sense of belonging and camaraderie amongst devotees and visitors alike. The proximity of Malegaon to Nanded also makes it a relevant location for those visiting the Sikh holy site of Hazur Sahib. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Isapur Dam " class="section">
            <h2>Isapur Dam </h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Isapur Dam " class="section-image">
            <p>Isapur Dam, also known as the Upper Painganga Dam, is a significant earthfill dam located on the Painganga River near Kalamnuri in Hingoli district, Maharashtra, India. Constructed in 1982, this impressive structure stands 57 meters tall and stretches 4,120.1 meters in length. It is primarily utilized for irrigation, serving the agricultural needs of Yavatmal, Hingoli, and Nanded districts. Isapur Dam is considered one of the largest dams in Maharashtra and is recognized for its picturesque natural surroundings, including forests and lush greenery. The area attracts nature enthusiasts and birdwatchers, especially during the winter months. Nearby attractions include the Painganga Wildlife Sanctuary, Shembaleshwar Temple, and Anchuleshwar Temple. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Shrikshetra Mahurgad" class="section">
            <h2>Shrikshetra Mahurgad</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Shrikshetra Mahurgad" class="section-image">
            <p>Shrikshetra Mahurgad, a revered pilgrimage destination in the Nanded district of Maharashtra, holds immense religious significance as the site of the Renuka Devi Temple, one of the Shakti Peethas. Legend has it that the head of Goddess Sati (manifesting as Renuka) fell here, making it a sacred spot for devotees of the Shaktism sect. Beyond the Renuka Devi Temple, Mahur also features temples dedicated to Lord Dattatreya, believed to be his birthplace, and Goddess Anusaya, his mother. The area boasts the historic Mahurgad Fort, offering panoramic views of the picturesque Sahyadri hills and valleys. Mahur's tranquil atmosphere, rich history, and the surrounding natural beauty, including teakwood forests and diverse wildlife like peacocks, deer, and panthers, make it a captivating blend of spirituality, history, and natural splendor. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Masjid of Biloli" class="section">
            <h2>Masjid of Biloli</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Masjid of Biloli" class="section-image">
            <p>Several important mosques are located in Biloli, a town in the Nanded district of Maharashtra, India. The most prominent among them is the Jama Masjid, often referred to as the the Kala Pathar Ki Masjid or Black Stone Mosque, due to its construction using dark-colored stone. This significant landmark is believed to have been built by Sarfaraz Khan, an officer in the Mughal Emperor Aurangzeb's army. Beyond this historical mosque, Biloli also boasts other notable mosques, such as Masjid a Nurool Huda located in Deshmukh Nagar, and the Masjid located in Biloli, which has a phone number (+91 96898 90022) for inquiries. The presence of these mosques highlights Biloli's role as a center of Islamic faith and heritage within the broader Nanded district, which is also known for its Sikh Gurudwaras. Visitors can explore these sites, along with other attractions in Nanded, particularly during the cooler winter months. </p>
        </section>

        <section id="Kinwat Forest" class="section">
            <h2>Kinwat Forest</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Kinwat Forest" class="section-image">
            <p>Kinwat Forest, nestled in the Nanded district of Maharashtra, is a significant natural area encompassing the Painganga Wildlife Sanctuary. This region is recognized for its diverse flora and fauna, thriving within a dry deciduous teak forest. The Painganga River plays a crucial role in the ecosystem, forming a natural border and nourishing the fertile soil, rich in decomposed leaves and animal matter. The sanctuary provides a home for various animals including tigers, leopards, sloth bears, deer, and a rich birdlife. Visitors can explore the forest's beauty and wildlife through activities like jungle safaris, particularly during the monsoon season when the landscape is most vibrant. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Waghala Aqueduct" class="section">
            <h2>Waghala Aqueduct</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Waghala Aqueduct" class="section-image">
            <p>The Waghala Aqueduct in Nanded is a historical gravity-fed water system constructed by Bhagwanrao Thatte Naik to address water scarcity. This aqueduct, designed in the Persian style, transports water from the Harsool River, located 12 kilometers away, to Nanded. Its innovative design utilizes a ceramic pipeline encased in stone and brick masonry, with six access points ("mambas") for maintenance. What makes the Waghala Aqueduct remarkable is its reliance on gravity alone, functioning without pumps or electricity to deliver water. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>
